the ideal world

Representative sample

  • systematic / random
  • for species mapping: planned surveys

Regardless the context in which you are working: when using observations to estimate a parameter, build or calibrate a model, you like these observations to be representative. Random or systematic sampling can be used to achieve this.

In the case of species mapping or discovery: one would plan the places to be visited prior to going to the field. Then both presences and absences would be recorded.

the real world

convenience sample

  • geographically unrepresentative
  • environmentally unrepresentative
  • selection bias

So presence-only observations are by definition not the result of random sampling, and do most likely not represent the geographical nor the environmental space well.

This problem is often denoted by the term (sample) selection bias

Selection bias

any harm done?

  • problem: where to select background/pseudo-absences?
  • risk: to model sampling effort, not ecology
  • questions: does it always matter (when)?

The concrete problem with presence-only data is where to place the background or pseudo-absences. This choice influences the resulting model and model predictions.

When choosing the entire prediction-domain as background, irrelevent environmental values may enter the model, leading to a model that predicts mostly were the species has been sampled.

The questions is how sensitive the results are to selection bias.

Selection bias

how to fix it

  • bias-correction grid
  • sub-sample (spatial filter)
  • restrict background to part of area
  • select in environmental space
  • stratify domain and fit different models

Fourcade et al. 2014 used these 5

  • bias grid: probability surface from where the background is sampled (proposed by Phillips et al. 2009)
  • sub-sampling: omit records, such that occurrences are regularly distributed in the geographical space
  • restrict: select bg. sample around presence locations
  • select in env. space: subsample records such that they occur evenly in environmental space
  • stratify domain: fit different models to different parts of the domain

Concrete case study

Kramer-Schadt et al. (2013)

  • Malay civet (2 species), Borneo
  • real & simulated data
  • no correction, correction grid (1) & sub-sample (2)

We'll look at results from three case-studies where experiments are done to see how selection bias influences the model results.

The first study, by Kramer-Schadt et al. 2013, uses real as well as artificial data for two species of civet cats from Borneo and compares two methods to correct for selection bias with 'no-correction'. Two different levels of 'sub-sampling' are used.

Kramer-Schadt et al. 2013 Figure 1.

Malay civet records per land-use category for the three data filtering approaches: no spatial filtering (SF-no, large figure); distance correction by taking only 1 point within a radius of 10 km shown for Sabah as example (SF-10, small inset left) and additional correction by taking proportionally as many records from Sabah as from the rest of Borneo (SF-bal, small inset middle).

Kramer-Schadt et al. 2013 Figure 2a.

MaxEnt spatial predictions for the Malay civet for different scenarios of data filtering [SF-no, SF-10, SF-bal], background manipulations [BM-no, BM-0.01], for varying model complexity (left or right columns). A threshold of Maxent-suitabaility index >0.5 is used to turn the map into binary predictions (suitable: black colour, unsuitable: grey colour).

Kramer-Schadt et al. 2013 Figure 2b.

MaxEnt spatial predictions for the Malay civet for different scenarios of data filtering [SF-no, SF-10, SF-bal], background manipulations [BM-no, BM-0.01], for varying model complexity (left or right columns). Here a 10th percentile training presence logistic threshold is used to turn the map into binary predictions (suitable: black colour, unsuitable: grey colour).

Kramer-Schadt et al. 2013 Figure 2c.

MaxEnt spatial predictions for the Malay civet for different scenarios of data filtering [SF-no, SF-10, SF-bal], background manipulations [BM-no, BM-0.01], for varying model complexity (left or right columns). Here a minimum training presence logistic threshold (MTP) is used to turn the map into binary predictions (suitable: black colour, unsuitable: grey colour).

Conclusions on bias correction

Kramer-Schadt et al. 2013

  • effects of bias-correction are large

  • spatial filtering works best, followed by correction grid

Kramer-Schadt et al. 2013

"If many occurrence records are available, our results demonstrate that spatial filtering and balancing of occurrence data are preferred relative to background manipulation. If only few spatially clustered occurrence records are available and spatial filtering is impossible, the manipulation of the background dataset seems to be the second best option."

Another case

Syfert, Smith, and Coomes (2013)

  • Tree ferns, New Zealand
  • real data (2 data sets!)
  • external data for validation
  • correction grid
Syfert et al. 2013 study the effect of sample selection and possibilities to correct it by using a correction grid. Two distinct data sets are used, studying the same group of tree fern species. Apart from cross-validation, an external data set is used toe validate the results.

Syfert et al. 2013 Figure 1. Data locations in New Zealand.

Tree fern occurrence locations (orange) and "absence" locations (blue) are based on a) herbarium data extracted from GBIF; b) NVS ecological survey data extracted from GBIF, and c) LUCAS plot data. In the case of the herbarium and NVS datasets, "absences" are background locations based on locations of other vascular plants; in the case of the LUCAS dataset, true absences are shown.

  • orange - background on basis of tree ferns
  • blue - background on basis of vascular plants
  • black - all NZ locatoins (1 km resolution)

Syfert et al. 2013 Figure 2. Density distribution plots of environmental variables.

Tree fern occurrences (orange) and background locations are based on locations of other vascular plants (blue) compared to all NZ locations (~1 km resolution; black) for the herbarium dataset (upper row) and the NVS dataset (lower row). Temperature seasonality is represented as standard deviations multiplied by 10.

Syfert et al. 2013 Figure 3 [captions of figures 3 and 4 are switched in paper] Box plots of AUC values. AUC values derived from MaxEnt models fitted using different functional forms ("feature types") and two different training datasets: herbarium (a-d) and NVS (e-h). Evaluations are made using randomly withheld test data without and with correcting geographical sampling bias (a & e) and (b & f), respectively; evaluations are made using independent LUCAS data without and with correcting for sampling bias are (c & g) and (d & h), respectively.

Conclusions on bias correction

Syfert et al. 2013

  • correction grid works well
  • effects are large
  • take care when evaluting 'bias-corrected models' on 'not bias-corrected data'
Syfert et al. 2013 A correction grid greatly improves the predictive performance of SDMs. The authors argue that geographic bias correction should become the default option in SDMs. The benefits of correcting for sampling bias were only apparent when model performance was assessed using independent presence-absence data! With 25% withheld data for model evaluation, predictive performance decreased when sampling bias corrections were introduced because the training and test datasets possess the same geographical sampling bias. Performance statistics derived from withheld data can therefore not be used to justify whether or not to correct for bias.

Last case

Fourcade et al. (2014)

  • turtle & salamander data (2 species) & one virtual species
  • different bias types, varying in degrees
  • 5 bias correction methods
  • AUC and 3 measures of overlap

Fourcade et al. 2014 study all five bias correction methods that were previously listed.

They define different types of biases and also vary the intensities of these biases over 3 levels.

To measure model performance, 3 performance metrics (measuring overlap between predicted and observed species range) are applied apart from AUC.

Fourcade et al. 2014 Figure 1. Workflow used in analyses. Original datasets of a virtual and 2 real species were altered to create 12 bias combining 4 bias types and 3 bias intensities. Five methods of sampling bias correction were employed to assess the improvement in the modeled distribution relative to the original distribution using MAXENT. Correction performance was assessed using AUC and 3 measures of overlap between the corrected the original unbiased model.

Fourcade et al. 2014 Figure 2. Locations of records used for modeling. (A) Virtual species; (B) Chrysemys picta; (C) Plethodon cylindraceus.

Fourcade et al. 2014 Figure 3. Generation of sampling bias for the virtual species.

To generate artificial sampling bias, the original dataset (here the virtual species) was altered into 4 different types of bias (rows), each with 3 intensities (columns).

Fourcade et al. 2014 Figure 4. Evaluation indices of biased models across bias intensities.

Reduction of AUC between unbiased and biased models (in percentage), Schoener's D overlaps between biased and unbiased models computed on SDMs (Dgeo) and in environmental space (Denv), and Gover the binary distribution overlap (mean SD). Dark grey bars: Chrysemys picta, light grey bars: Plethodon cylindraceus, black bars: virtual species.

Fourcade et al. 2014 Figure 5. Rank of each method to correct sampling bias.

Mean ranks standard-error for the performance of each method to correct sampling bias for each species (Chrysemys picta: left, Plethodon cylindraceus: center, virtual species: right), following 3 measures of correction performance: \(\Delta\)AUC (left), \(\Delta\)Dgeo (centre), and \(\Delta\)Gover (right). For each type of bias and bias intensity, the method which results in the most efficient correction is set to 1 whereas the least powerful method is set to 5. The plotted values are the mean rank across the 4 types of bias and 3 intensities.

Conclusions on bias correction

Fourcade et al. 2014

  • sub-sampling worked best for different species & bias type
  • effects are large but differ per error metric

Fourcade et al. 2014 do not present a concise conclusion.

Different from the previous case-studies, here the differences among the various error metrics are emphasized.

But regardless of that sub-sampling worked well across the different species, bias types & error metrics.

A weak point in this study is the lack of a validation strategy on independent data or a subset of the data.

Overall conclusion

  • so … do correct selection bias with:
    • sub-sample
    • correction grid

It seems always a good idea to apply some sort of bias correction.

Sub-sampling appeared as the preferred method from the case studies, followed by applying a correction grid.

Still, it goes against my nature to throw-away data and sub-sampling will not work for cases with relatively few observations.

A work-around could be to use data-weights (if the modeling method would allow to do so) one would assign low weights to presences in high-density areas.

Discussion points & questions

  • nothing more practical than a good theory, … but can we build it?
  • will more case studies help?
  • how could ZON help?
  • ZON could help by f.i. rerunning these case studies, but now using the same indices and same metrics
  • People could add their indices and/or different bias correction methods.
  • In that way the knowledge burried in multiple case studies can be more readily interpreted and accumulate to a (hopefully) consistent overall picture.
  • Eventually we may have a sufficiently large knowledge base to develop a theory on selection bias and build bias correction methods from first principles.
